							<h1>The Origins of Chinatowns in America</h1>

								<p>
                                <br>
								The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882, and its successive act, the Geary Laws in 1892, were the sole American legislation explicitly banning immigration for entire racial groups. These laws were primarily driven by a fear of low-cost Chinese labor driving down wages for white Americans, not only in the railroads - where Chinese immigrants of the period are stereotypically shown working, but also in agricultural labor and during California’s Gold Rush.  
								<br> <br />
								The new laws prevented Chinese families from emigrating to join their male family members who had been working here in the US, largely due to suspicion of Chinese women coming to the US to work in prostitution. Combined with laws meant to keep Chinese from intermarrying with whites, this was meant less to prevent Chinese from staying in the country - and more to drive them ‘back to China’.
								<br> <br />
								One of the few ways around this law was a ‘merchant exclusion’, which allowed individuals and families who were opening or running a business to stay in and move to the US. This resulted in a large number of Chinese restaurants opening up all over the US - one of the few good things to come out of a dark time in Chinese-American history.
								<br> <br />
								However, others who are not part of this group have complained about the loud music and dancing, saying it disrupts their concentration and daily life. In Guangzhou, citizens have proposed a ban on dancing altogether, albeit with fierce resistance from the damas. They argue that there is nothing wrong with dancing in a public place, yet detractors say otherwise. 
								<br> <br />
								As CW Chan observed in his interview with us, some things don’t change in modern times. “Food industry is a very important industry, and I’ll try to put it in the context of the growth of Chinatown. In the early days, Chinatown was only restaurants, grocery stores. If you don’t do anything else, you have to eat. Everybody has to eat. That’s how the immigrants get their first step in the community. Restaurant is a very important part of the Chinese American culture. In the old days, international students, we had no money. I came to Chicago to go to UC, before school started, I was working at a restaurant, making money. So all the Chinese Americans, everybody had some link to the food industry, because that’s how you survive. That’s the survival of the immigrant community”. 
						        </p>
